@Article{Fang_AM_2010_Stability,
  author       = {C.M. Fang and M.A. van Huis and M.H.F. Sluiter and H.W. Zandbergen},
  journal      = {Acta Mater.},
  title        = {Stability, structure and electronic properties of $\gamma$-Fe23C6 from first-principles theory},
  year         = {2010},
  month        = {5},
  number       = {8},
  pages        = {2968--2977},
  volume       = {58},
  comment      = {VASP PAW GGA PBE
500 eV
DFT+U

$\gamma$-Fe23C6

It is generally known that carbon exhibits at least two phases, graphite and diamond. The ground state of carbon is graphite. Experiments have determined that graphite is about 17meV atom–1 more stable than diamond [20]. Graphite exhibits a layered structure. The interlayer bond- ing in graphite is largely determined by van der Waals interactions, which is not correctly described by conven- tional density functional theory (DFT) methods [21]. On the other hand, the DFT works well for diamond [22]. Therefore, we performed calculations for diamond and subtracted the 17 meV atom–1 correction term in order to obtain the enthalpy for graphite.

As screening is not fully developed inside the atomic d-shell of Fe, we also considered the GGA + U approach, using two formulations: that of Lichtenstein et al. [31] (Hubbard U = 2.2 eV Stoner J = 0.9 eV) and that of Cococcioni and de Gironcoli [32] (U = 2.2 eV, J = 0 eV).

The cut-off energy of the augmentation functions was about 644.8 eV.

The GGA + U approaches predict also that the θ-Fe3C phase is stable while $\gamma$-Fe23C6 is metastable with respect to the elemental solids ($\alpha$-Fe and graphite), in contrast with the GGA, which has both carbides as metastable phases.

Fe23C6: DOS is obviously metalic},
  creationdate = {2019-12-20Τ17:08:36},
  doi          = {10.1016/j.actamat.2010.01.025},
  file         = {:Fang_AM_2010_Stability.pdf:PDF},
  keywords     = {Fe23C6},
  publisher    = {Elsevier {BV}},
}

